<rails_security_guide>
<title>RUBY ON RAILS SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Ruby on Rails applications have framework-specific vulnerabilities including mass assignment, strong parameters bypass, CSRF token issues, session fixation, render template injection, and ActiveRecord injection. Focus on Rails-specific patterns and conventions that lead to security flaws.</critical>

<scope>
- Mass assignment vulnerabilities
- Strong parameters bypass
- CSRF token prediction and bypass
- Session fixation and hijacking
- Render template injection (ERB, Haml)
- ActiveRecord injection (SQL, NoSQL)
- Route manipulation and constraint bypass
- Insecure deserialization (YAML, Marshal)
- File upload vulnerabilities (ActiveStorage)
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify Rails version and gems (check headers, error pages, Gemfile.lock)
2. Map routes and controllers (rails routes, analyze JavaScript)
3. Test strong parameters enforcement
4. Probe CSRF token generation and validation
5. Test template rendering for injection
6. Analyze ActiveRecord queries for injection
7. Examine session handling and cookie security
</methodology>

<mass_assignment>
<concept>
{% raw %}
# Rails allows assigning multiple attributes at once
# Without proper filtering, users can modify unintended fields

# Vulnerable code:
def create
  @user = User.new(params[:user])
  @user.save
end

# Attack:
POST /users
{
  "user": {
    "email": "attacker@evil.com",
    "password": "password123",
    "role": "admin",      // Unintended field
    "is_verified": true,  // Unintended field
    "balance": 999999     // Unintended field
  }
}

# Result: User created with admin role and high balance
{% endraw %}
</concept>

<detection>
{% raw %}
# Look for vulnerable patterns in code/responses

# Old Rails (< 4.0) used attr_accessible
# Modern Rails uses strong parameters

# Check error messages:
POST /users {"user": {"email": "test@example.com", "admin": true}}
# Error: "Unpermitted parameter: admin"
# -> Strong parameters enforced (good)

# No error -> Vulnerable to mass assignment

# Blind testing:
# Create account with extra fields
# Check if fields were set (profile page, API response)
{% endraw %}
</detection>

